# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Exhumer is a fifty-five-ton medium BattleMech developed by Independence Weaponry on Quentin during the waning years of the Republic of the Sphere. First entering production in 3129, the design was conceived as a long-range fire support platform mounted on a fast and well-protected medium chassis. Intended to fill the Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery's need for a modern medium striker, the Exhumer instead found its greatest success on the mercenary market after the DCMS declined to continue procurement. The design has earned a mixed reputation, respected for its speed and protection but dogged by early reliability concerns that took years to overcome.</p>
capabilities:<p>Built around a Hermes 330 XL engine, the Exhumer achieves a top speed of 97 kph, making it one of the faster designs in its weight class. An EXR endo steel frame maximizes available payload, while ten and a half tons of New Samarkand Royal ferro-fibrous armor supplemented by CASE II ammunition protection gives the design solid survivability for its tonnage. The absence of jump jets reflects the intended role as a mobile fire support platform rather than a close-range brawler.</p><p>The primary armament consists of a pair of Diverse Optics 30X extended-range large lasers mounted in the arms, providing significant long-range striking power. These are supported by twin LongFire V LRM-5 launchers and a Shigunga MRM-10, offering supplemental missile fire at varying engagement distances. However, the integration of surplus Garret communications and targeting systems proved to be the design's greatest weakness. Poor synchronization between the Garret D2j targeting system and the multiple missile launchers resulted in persistent accuracy problems that plagued early production models. The Exhumer's loadout clearly favors stand-off engagements, making the inclusion of prominent battle fists something of a design contradiction, though mercenary operators have found these melee weapons surprisingly useful when engagements close unexpectedly.</p>
deployment:<p>Developed by Independence Weaponry specifically for the mercenary market beginning in 3131, this variant completely reworks the Exhumer for short-range combat. Replacing the original's long-range laser armament with pulse lasers and swapping the missile array for lighter short-range launchers, the variant's defining feature is its Triple Strength Myomer system, which dramatically enhances physical combat capability when operating at elevated temperatures. The EXR-3P proved highly popular among mercenary commands, offering a radically different tactical profile from the troubled original while retaining the same reliable chassis and power plant. Its success played a significant role in rehabilitating the Exhumer name on the mercenary market.</p>
history:<p>The Exhumer's origins are inextricably linked to the political ambitions of Benjamin District Warlord Mitsura Sakamoto, who championed the design for over a decade before it finally entered production. Sakamoto, an engineer by training, became personally invested in the project and envisioned the Exhumer supplanting aging workhorses like the Dragon and Thunderbolt in front-line DCMS service. He used his considerable political influence to push the design through the procurement process, and when the first production models rolled off Independence Weaponry's lines on Quentin and were assigned to the Second Benjamin Regulars in 3129, Sakamoto's vision appeared close to realization.</p><p>Early deployments along the Dominion and Republic borders quickly revealed a critical flaw. The surplus targeting and communications systems suffered from poor integration with the missile armament, and combat reports from raids on worlds such as Dehgolan documented repeated targeting failures that left MechWarriors unable to reliably engage at range. These problems proved embarrassing enough that Sakamoto was forced to order a comprehensive electronic overhaul of all fielded Exhumers, a costly admission of the design's shortcomings.</p><p>The DCMS subsequently canceled its remaining Exhumer orders, and Independence Weaponry pivoted to marketing the design to mercenary buyers. This transition proved fortuitous for the manufacturer. Despite the targeting issues, the Exhumer was better received among mercenary forces who valued the chassis's speed, armor protection, and relatively affordable price point. Mercenary commands such as Gannon's Cannons employed the Exhumer effectively in strike and garrison operations across the Draconis Combine's frontier, demonstrating that the design had genuine combat potential when operated by experienced MechWarriors willing to work around its electronic shortcomings.</p><p>Operating from Quentin, which passed from Republic of the Sphere control to independent status and eventually Draconis Combine authority during the tumultuous Dark Age period, Independence Weaponry continued developing the chassis. The introduction of a close-combat-oriented variant in 3131 demonstrated the manufacturer's responsiveness to market demands, and its popularity among mercenary commands helped rehabilitate the Exhumer's reputation. By the ilClan era, continued production under Combine oversight on Quentin ensured a steady supply of Exhumer variants to mercenary and Combine forces alike.</p>
